Equating the right hand side of Eq.(\ref{Host_width}) to zero, one can easily obtain the criterion for the host ribbon presence in the structure for each type of JGNRs: Z60 $\ell \geq 2w$, Z120 $\ell \geq 2 w$, A60 $\ell > 2 w/3$, A120 $\ell \geq 2w$. Such simple mapping of JGNR onto ordinary straight GNRs is only possible in symmetric case when $\ell_1 = \ell_2$. As for the asymmetric case, it is more complicated, because the effective, the host and the straight ribbons become specific JGNRs with low values of indexes. Additionally, this mapping would be of no practical use for ribbons from the same class that can be compared straightforwardly.


